pr_title: Add command line options for saving and exporting
pr_body:
Hi. I changed `app.py` to support saving the project when importing and also for directly exporting to STL the surface generating using all the predefined presets for the masks. This allows to automatically generate the models from the images, without using the GUI. I thought it would be useful for other people too, that's why I'm creating this PR.

I also created a Dockerfile, so the environment can be easily replicated in any computer with Docker.

Any suggestion regarding refactorings or the API for the command line is welcome :smile: 

btw, is there a way to use this command line options without opening a GUI? So it can be used through SSH or Docker without a display being set.

## 🧪 How to test this Pull Request
<!-- If applicable, please describe how to test the changes made in this PR -->
1. pre-commit should work after installing it. Write the following commands if you don't have precommit.

Install using pip:
```console
pip install pre-commit
pre-commit install
```
Or Install using conda:
```console
conda install -c conda-forge pre-commit
pre-commit install
```
2. try making an empty commit using `git commit --allow-empty -m "testing". You should see a similar message to the following.
![image](https://github.com/invesalius/invesalius3/assets/113486195/9ac107db-711c-4895-8270-e373eaba1954)
3. For running pre-commit against all files (formatting and ordering all imports). Run the command
```console
pre-commit run --all-files
```

None

Command used to create container from image: `docker run -it --privileged --env="DISPLAY" --network=host --volume="$HOME/.Xauthority:/root/.Xauthority:rw" <image-name> bash`

pr_title: UPD: Update conda and pip packages for Python 3.11
pr_body:
Update several relevant package versions in both conda and environment.

This solves issues with installation in MacOS due to old version of rtmidi.

It also bumps vtk, nibabel, pyacvd, and several other packages to the latest version.

I tried to test the new numpy 2.0, but raised errors on cython compilation due to deprecated IF in pyxd file. So, I leaving this update to a later stage.

I tested in MacOS Sonoma with conda and pip installations and image loading, tractography, debug navigation are working fine.

Known issue:

I could not create a surface after brain segmentation which raised the following error:

![image](https://github.com/invesalius/invesalius3/assets/1081406/ab0e5bd5-d0e4-48b8-801a-a2d1aa261cbf)

@tfmoraes can you test it, please?
